trans-unit.source: Normalize Data
trans-unit.target: Normalize Data

trans-unit.source: Rescales numeric data to constrain dataset values to a standard range
trans-unit.target: Rescales numeric data to constrain dataset values to a standard range

trans-unit.target: Category: <legacyLink xlink:href="345C5ED4-4DD6-4998-9773-6CA0E00E6946" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink">Data Transformation / Scale and Reduce</legacyLink>

trans-unit.source: Module Overview
trans-unit.target: Module Overview

trans-unit.source: You can use the <ui>Normalize Data</ui> module to transform a dataset so that the columns in the dataset are on a common scale.
trans-unit.target: You can use the <ui>Normalize Data</ui> module to transform a dataset so that the columns in the dataset are on a common scale.

trans-unit.source: For example, the input dataset might contain columns with very different values, which can cause problems when you combine the values as features during modeling.
trans-unit.target: For example, the input dataset might contain columns with very different values, which can cause problems when you combine the values as features during modeling.

trans-unit.source: By transforming the values so that they maintain their general distribution and rations, yet confirm to a common scale, you can generally get better results when modeling.
trans-unit.target: By transforming the values so that they maintain their general distribution and rations, yet confirm to a common scale, you can generally get better results when modeling.

trans-unit.source: You can apply normalization to a single column, or to multiple columns in the same dataset.
trans-unit.target: You can apply normalization to a single column, or to multiple columns in the same dataset.

trans-unit.source: You can also save the normalization steps you define in this module as a transformation that can be applied to other datasets.
trans-unit.target: You can also save the normalization steps you define in this module as a transformation that can be applied to other datasets.

trans-unit.source: Some algorithms require that data be normalized before training a model.
trans-unit.target: Some algorithms require that data be normalized before training a model.

trans-unit.source: Other algorithms perform their own data scaling or normalization.
trans-unit.target: Other algorithms perform their own data scaling or normalization.

trans-unit.source: Review the data requirements of the algorithm before using the data to train a model.
trans-unit.target: Review the data requirements of the algorithm before using the data to train a model.

trans-unit.source: How to Configure Normalize Data
trans-unit.target: How to Configure Normalize Data

trans-unit.source: Use Column Selector to choose the numeric columns to normalize.
trans-unit.target: Use Column Selector to choose the numeric columns to normalize.

trans-unit.source: By default, the Column Selector chooses all numeric columns.
trans-unit.target: By default, the Column Selector chooses all numeric columns.

trans-unit.source: However, you must apply the same normalization process to all selected columns.
trans-unit.target: However, you must apply the same normalization process to all selected columns.

trans-unit.source: If you want to use a different normalization method with different columns, you need to use different instances of <ui>Normalize Data</ui>.
trans-unit.target: If you want to use a different normalization method with different columns, you need to use different instances of <ui>Normalize Data</ui>.

trans-unit.source: Choose a mathematical function from the <ui>Transformation method</ui> option to apply to the selected columns.
trans-unit.target: Choose a mathematical function from the <ui>Transformation method</ui> option to apply to the selected columns.

trans-unit.source: Run the experiment.
trans-unit.target: Run the experiment.

trans-unit.source: Optionally, you can save the normalization process as a transformation.
trans-unit.target: Optionally, you can save the normalization process as a transformation.

trans-unit.source: Just right-click the right-hand output port and select Save as Transform.
trans-unit.target: Just right-click the right-hand output port and select Save as Transform.

trans-unit.source: You can then load the saved transformations from the Transforms group of the left navigation pane and apply it to a dataset with the same schema by using <link xlink:href="805e592d-0f1f-48eb-97c9-688ed0c1dc70" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink">apply Transformation</link>.
trans-unit.target: You can then load the saved transformations from the Transforms group of the left navigation pane and apply it to a dataset with the same schema by using <link xlink:href="805e592d-0f1f-48eb-97c9-688ed0c1dc70" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink">apply Transformation</link>.

trans-unit.source: MinMax
trans-unit.target: MinMax

trans-unit.source: The min-max normalizer linearly rescales every feature to the [0,1] interval.
trans-unit.target: The min-max normalizer linearly rescales every feature to the [0,1] interval.

trans-unit.source: Rescaling to the [0,1] interval is done by shifting the values of each feature so that the minimal value is 0, and then dividing by the new maximal value (which is the difference between the original maximal and minimal values).

trans-unit.source: Technical Notes
trans-unit.target: Technical Notes

trans-unit.source: In linear classification algorithms, instances are viewed as vectors in multi-dimensional space.
trans-unit.target: In linear classification algorithms, instances are viewed as vectors in multi-dimensional space.

trans-unit.source: Since the range of values of raw data varies widely, some objective functions do not work properly without normalization.
trans-unit.target: Since the range of values of raw data varies widely, some objective functions do not work properly without normalization.

trans-unit.source: For example, if one of the features has a broad range of values, the distances between points is governed by this particular feature.
trans-unit.target: For example, if one of the features has a broad range of values, the distances between points is governed by this particular feature.

trans-unit.source: Therefore, numeric features should be normalized so that each feature contributes approximately proportionately to the final distance.
trans-unit.target: Therefore, numeric features should be normalized so that each feature contributes approximately proportionately to the final distance.

trans-unit.source: This can provide significant speedup and accuracy benefits.
trans-unit.target: This can provide significant speedup and accuracy benefits.

trans-unit.source: When using the Logistic Regression and Averaged Perceptron algorithms, the default is to normalize features before training.
trans-unit.target: When using the Logistic Regression and Averaged Perceptron algorithms, the default is to normalize features before training.
